# AI Documentation Synchronization

When implementing or reviewing changes, keep AI-maintained docs in sync with the real codebase.

## Covered files

`ai/PROJECT_CONTEXT.md`, `ai/AI_RULES.md`, and `.cursor/rules/`.

(`CURRENT_STATE.md`, `ARCHITECTURE_DECISIONS.md`, `TASK_TEMPLATE.md`, and `PROMPT_PATTERNS.md` are intentionally not maintained — see `PROJECT_CONTEXT.md` §20.)

## Update docs when changes affect

Architecture, features, APIs, database models, environment variables, workflows, setup steps, dependencies, risky systems (backup/sync/crypto), conventions, deployment behavior, auth/permissions, or major refactors.

## Agent behavior

- Update affected documentation **as part of implementation work** when triggers apply.
- **Inspect implementation first** — do not update docs blindly.
- Prefer **incremental section edits** over full rewrites.
- **Preserve useful historical context** (migrations, rationale) unless factually wrong.
- **Minimize stale docs** — fix or remove outdated claims in the same task when practical.
- Cross-link instead of duplicating large sections across files.

## Avoid

- Leaving architecture or workflow docs stale after behavioral changes
- Rewriting unrelated documentation sections
- Documenting non-existent features without marking them as planned

Full policy: [`AI_RULES.md`](../../ai/AI_RULES.md)
